---
import BaseHead from '../components/BaseHead.astro';
import CodeSnippet from '../components/CodeSnippet.astro';
import Footer from '../components/Footer.astro';
import Header from '../components/Header.astro';
import { SITE_DESCRIPTION, SITE_TITLE } from '../consts';
---

<!doctype html>
<html lang="en">
	<head>
		<BaseHead title={SITE_TITLE} description={SITE_DESCRIPTION} />
	</head>
	<body>
		<Header />
		<main class="landing">
			<section class="hero">
				<h1>Global workflows for LLM agents</h1>
				<p class="hero-copy">
					ZipperGen is a Python DSL and runtime for multi-agent LLM systems.
					You write one global protocol: who talks to whom, who calls tools or LLMs,
					and who owns each decision. ZipperGen projects the protocol to local agents
					and runs them concurrently.
				</p>
				<p class="hero-copy hero-copy-sub">
					Coordination is explicit, inspectable, and deadlock-free by construction.
				</p>
				<div class="hero-actions">
					<a class="button primary" href="https://github.com/zippergen-io/zippergen">View on GitHub</a>
					<a class="button secondary" href="/demo">Try the demo</a>
					<a class="button secondary" href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2604.17612">Read the paper</a>
					<a href="https://github.com/zippergen-io/paper-isola/tree/main/Lean">
						<img src="/lean-formalized.svg" alt="Lean formalized" height="34" />
					</a>
					<a href="https://github.com/zippergen-io/paper-isola/tree/main/Lean">
						<img src="/lean.svg" alt="Lean verified" height="34" />
					</a>
				</div>
				<figure class="hero-shot">
					<img
						src="/zipperchat-msc.png"
						alt="ZipperChat MSC view showing lifeline columns with action, message, and decision cards"
					/>
				</figure>
				<figure class="hero-shot">
					<img
						src="/zipperchat-dialog.png"
						alt="ZipperChat detail view with email context on the left and a draft reply form on the right"
					/>
					<figcaption>Clicking a human action opens a detail view. You can review the context and respond.</figcaption>
				</figure>
			</section>

			<section class="feature-grid" aria-label="Core properties">
				<article>
					<h2>Global protocols</h2>
					<p>Write the coordination once: messages, decisions, tools, LLM calls, and human approval points.</p>
				</article>
				<article>
					<h2>Local agents</h2>
					<p>ZipperGen projects the protocol to one local program per lifeline. Each agent receives only the sends, receives, decisions, and actions it needs.</p>
				</article>
				<article>
					<h2>Concurrent runtime</h2>
					<p>The projected agents run concurrently. The generated coordination code preserves the message structure of the protocol.</p>
				</article>
				<article>
					<h2>Inspectable execution</h2>
					<p>Runs can be inspected as message sequence charts in ZipperChat.</p>
				</article>
				<article class="feature-wide">
					<h2>Formal core</h2>
					<p>The projection is based on <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Message_sequence_chart">Message Sequence Charts</a> and <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Choreographic_programming">choreographic programming</a>. The core deadlock-freedom theorem is machine-checked in Lean 4. The implementation is on <a href="https://github.com/zippergen-io/zippergen">GitHub</a>.</p>
					<p class="formal-refs">Bollig, Függer, Nowak. <em>Provable Coordination for LLM Agents via Message Sequence Charts.</em> <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2604.17612">arXiv:2604.17612 [cs.PL]</a></p>
					<p class="formal-refs">Bollig. <em>Causal Past Logic for Runtime Verification of Distributed LLM Agent Workflows.</em> <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2605.20923">arXiv:2605.20923 [cs.LO]</a></p>
				</article>
			</section>

			<section class="split-section">
				<div>
					<p class="section-label">Example: branching with an owner</p>
					<h2>Branching with an owner.</h2>
					<p>
						The annotation <code>@ Editor</code> says that Editor owns the decision. ZipperGen
						generates the control communication needed by the other lifelines.
					</p>
				</div>
				<CodeSnippet
					code={`@workflow
def write_tweet(topic: str @ User) -> str:
    User(topic) >> Writer(topic)
    Writer: tweet = draft(topic)
    Writer(tweet) >> Editor(tweet)
    Editor: approved = approve(tweet)

    if approved @ Editor:
        Editor(tweet) >> User(tweet)
    else:
        Editor(tweet) >> Writer(tweet)
        Writer: tweet = revise(tweet)
        Writer(tweet) >> User(tweet)

    return tweet @ User`}
				/>
			</section>

			<section class="split-section">
				<div>
					<p class="section-label">Example: command center</p>
					<h2>Two parallel loops, shared agents.</h2>
					<p>
						<code>Calendar</code>, <code>Writer</code>, and <code>User</code> are shared lifelines.
						ZipperGen's projection ensures each receives exactly the messages it needs from
						whichever branch generated them.
					</p>
					<p><a href="https://github.com/zippergen-io/zippergen/blob/main/examples/command_center.py">Full source on GitHub</a></p>
				</div>
				<CodeSnippet
					code={`@workflow
def command_center():
    with parallel:
        with branch:
            email_loop()
        with branch:
            chat_loop()`}
				/>
			</section>

			<section class="split-section">
				<div>
					<p class="section-label">Runtime guards</p>
					<h2>Reading causally current state.</h2>
					<p>
						Guards can read the latest causally visible state instead of a sequential log.
						Vector clocks and message-carried views make the guard result depend on the
						asynchronous communication structure.
					</p>
				</div>
				<CodeSnippet
					code={`latest_device_on = At[Device].on == True

if latest_device_on @ Indicator:
    ...`}
				/>
			</section>

			<section class="quick-start">
				<div>
					<p class="section-label">Run locally</p>
					<h2>Run the first examples without API keys.</h2>
					<p>
						The built-in mock backend returns placeholder model outputs. To use real model
						calls, set the provider to OpenAI, Mistral, or Claude with one configuration
						line. ZipperGen also accepts OpenAI-compatible local model servers such as vLLM.
					</p>
				</div>
				<CodeSnippet
					lang="bash"
					code={`git clone https://github.com/zippergen-io/zippergen.git
cd zippergen
pip install -e .

python examples/hello.py                 # two lifelines, one LLM call
python examples/command_center.py --mock # email triage + Telegram commands
python examples/parallel.py              # fan-out / fan-in across branches`}
				/>
			</section>

			<section class="cta-section">
				<h2>Start from the examples.</h2>
				<p>
					Inspect the generated message sequence chart and decide whether
					global protocols fit your agent system.
				</p>
				<div class="hero-actions">
					<a class="button primary" href="https://github.com/zippergen-io/zippergen">Get the code</a>
					<a class="button secondary" href="/about">About the project</a>
				</div>
			</section>
		</main>
		<Footer />
	</body>
</html>

<style>
	.landing {
		width: 100%;
		max-width: none;
		padding: 0;
		overflow-x: hidden;
	}

	.landing :global(pre) {
		margin: 0;
	}

	.hero,
	.feature-grid,
	.split-section,
	.bands,
	.quick-start,
	.cta-section {
		width: min(1120px, calc(100% - 2rem));
		margin: 0 auto;
	}

	.hero {
		padding: 5.5rem 0 3rem;
	}

	.section-label {
		margin: 0 0 0.75rem;
		color: var(--accent-dark);
		font-size: 0.82rem;
		font-weight: 700;
		letter-spacing: 0;
		text-transform: uppercase;
	}

	.hero h1 {
		margin: 0;
		font-size: clamp(2rem, 3.8vw, 3.25rem);
		line-height: 1.1;
		white-space: nowrap;
	}

	.hero-copy {
		max-width: 760px;
		margin: 1.35rem 0 0;
		color: rgb(var(--gray-dark));
		font-size: 1.16rem;
		line-height: 1.65;
	}

	.hero-copy-sub {
		margin-top: 0.85rem;
	}

	.hero-actions {
		display: flex;
		flex-wrap: wrap;
		gap: 0.75rem;
		align-items: center;
		margin-top: 1.6rem;
	}

	.button {
		display: inline-flex;
		align-items: center;
		justify-content: center;
		min-height: 2.75rem;
		padding: 0 1.1rem;
		border-radius: 6px;
		font-weight: 600;
		text-decoration: none;
	}

	.button.primary {
		background: rgb(var(--black));
		color: white;
	}

	.button.secondary {
		border: 1px solid rgba(var(--gray), 0.28);
		background: white;
		color: rgb(var(--black));
	}

	.hero-actions img {
		display: block;
		border-radius: 0;
	}

	.hero-shot {
		margin: 3rem 0 0;
	}

	.hero-shot img {
		display: block;
		width: 100%;
		border: 1px solid rgba(var(--gray), 0.2);
		border-radius: 8px;
		box-shadow: 0 22px 55px rgba(19, 31, 45, 0.12);
	}

	.hero-shot figcaption {
		margin-top: 0.75rem;
		font-size: 0.9rem;
		color: rgb(var(--gray));
		text-align: center;
	}

	.feature-grid {
		display: grid;
		grid-template-columns: repeat(2, minmax(0, 1fr));
		gap: 1rem;
		padding: 1rem 0 3rem;
	}

	.feature-grid article {
		border: 1px solid rgba(var(--gray), 0.18);
		border-radius: 8px;
		background: white;
		padding: 1.15rem;
	}

	.feature-grid article.feature-wide {
		grid-column: 1 / -1;
	}

	.feature-grid h2 {
		margin-bottom: 0.4rem;
		font-size: 1.25rem;
	}

	.feature-grid p,
	.quick-start p,
	.cta-section p,
	.split-section p {
		color: rgb(var(--gray-dark));
	}

	.formal-refs {
		margin-top: 0.6rem;
		font-size: 0.85rem;
	}

	.quick-start h2,
	.cta-section h2,
	.split-section h2 {
		font-size: clamp(1.7rem, 4vw, 2.6rem);
	}

	.split-section,
	.quick-start {
		display: grid;
		grid-template-columns: minmax(0, 0.78fr) minmax(0, 1.22fr);
		gap: 2rem;
		align-items: start;
		padding: 4rem 0 2rem;
	}

	.cta-section {
		padding: 4rem 0 5rem;
	}

	@media (max-width: 840px) {
		.hero {
			padding-top: 3.25rem;
		}

		.feature-grid,
		.split-section,
		.quick-start {
			grid-template-columns: 1fr;
		}

		.feature-grid article.feature-wide {
			grid-column: 1;
		}

		.split-section,
		.quick-start,
		.cta-section {
			padding: 2.75rem 0;
		}
	}

	@media (max-width: 600px) {
		.hero h1 {
			white-space: normal;
			font-size: clamp(1.7rem, 8vw, 2.4rem);
		}

		.hero {
			padding-top: 2.25rem;
			padding-bottom: 2rem;
		}

		.hero-copy {
			font-size: 1rem;
		}

		.split-section,
		.quick-start,
		.cta-section {
			padding: 2rem 0;
		}
	}
</style>
